","Wiggenhall Saint Peter, Norfolk, England":"Wiggenhall St Peter, Norfolk, England","Wiggenhall St Peter, Norfolk, England":"Wiggenhall St Peter, Norfolk, England"},"nl":{"1165–1239":"1165–1239","1164–Male":"1164–Overleden","1169–1201":"1169–1201","1185–1227":"1185–1227","1140–1165":"1140–1165","1145–1219":"1145–1219","1165":"1165","1164":"1164","1185":"1185","1140":"1140","1239":"1239","1227":"1227","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1169":"1169","1201":"1201","1145":"1145","before 1185":"vóór 1185","1219":"1219","England":"England","Wiggenhall Saint Peter, Norfolk, England":"Wiggenhall St Peter, Norfolk, England","Wiggenhall St Peter, Norfolk, England":"Wiggenhall St Peter, Norfolk, England"},"en":{"1165–1239":"1165–1239","1164–Male":"1164–Deceased","1169–1201":"1169–1201","1185–1227":"1185–1227","1140–1165":"1140–1165","1145–1219":"1145–1219","1165":"1165","1164":"1164","1185":"1185","1140":"1140","1239":"1239","1227":"1227","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1169":"1169","1201":"1201","1145":"1145","before 1185":"before 1185","1219":"1219","England":"England","Wiggenhall Saint Peter, Norfolk, England":"Wiggenhall St Peter, Norfolk, England","Wiggenhall St Peter, Norfolk, England":"Wiggenhall St Peter, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Howard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, from the Middle English personal names <i>Huward</i> (also <i>Howard</i>) and <i>Heward</i>, from Old French <i>Huard</i> (itself from ancient Germanic <i>Hugihard</i>, <i>hugi-</i> ‘mind, understanding, spirit’ + <i>hard-</i> ‘hardy, bold’). As <i>Hugh</i> appears in Middle English as both <i>How</i> and <i>Hew</i>, this is the definite origin of <i>Heward</i> and a source of <i>Howard</i>. This surname is also very common among African Americans. See   Hugh  .","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Haward</i> or <i>Howard</i>, usually an Anglicized form of Old Danish <i>Hāwarth</i> (Old Norse <i>Hávarthr</i>, from <i>há</i> ‘high’ + <i>varthr</i> ‘guard, guardian, warden’). Alternation between <i>Haward</i> and <i>Howard</i> may have led to later confusion with   Hayward  .","English: occasionally a variant of   Ewart   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Fogarty","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, James Patrick, Kieran, Seamus, Siobhan.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Fógartaigh</b> ‘son of <i>Fógartach</i>’, a personal name from <i>fógartha</i> ‘proclaimed, banished, outlawed’. It is sometimes Anglicized as   Howard  ."]},{"name":"Huggard","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, from the medieval personal name <i>Hugard</i>, a variant of <i>Huard</i> (see   Howard  ). This surname is also established in Ireland (Kerry)."]},{"name":"Heward","meanings":["English: variant of   Howard  ."]},{"name":"Hayward","meanings":["English:","occupational name from Middle English <i>hayward</i> ‘keeper of the hedges and enclosures’ (Old English <i>hēgweard</i>), a manorial officer in charge of the common fields who protected corn and hay from cattle, theft, or damage, and supervised the harvest.","occasionally a variant of   Howard  ."]},{"name":"Huard","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Aime, Adelard, Jacques, Jean-Pierre, Lucien, Marcel, Alcide, Amiee, Armand, Aurele, Clermont, Fernard.","French and Channel Islands (Jersey): from the Old French personal name <i>Huart</i>, either identical in origin with   Howard   1 or a pet form of Old French   Hue  .","History: Jean Huard from Courson-Monteloup in Essonne, France, married Anne-Marie Amiot in Quebec City, QC, in 1670."]},{"name":"Hugh","meanings":["English, Welsh, and Scottish (of Norman origin): from the Old French personal name <i>Hue</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Hugo</i> (ultimately derived from <i>hugi-</i> ‘mind, spirit’). This was a very popular name in England after the Norman Conquest, partly due to the reputation of Saint Hugh of Lincoln (1140–1200), who was born in Burgundy and who established the first Carthusian monastery in England.","Scottish and Irish: adopted as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic personal name <i>Aodh</i>, a derivative of a Gaelic word meaning ‘fire’. See   Hughes  .","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surnames 邱 and 丘, based on their Hakka pronunciation; see   Qiu   1 and 2."]}]},{"name":"Alan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":50,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":59,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Alan Howard was born in 1165, in Wiggenhall St Peter, Norfolk, England, his father, Galfridus Howard, was 26 and his mother, Emma Jones, was 20. He married Wilburga Duchess Of Norfolk before 1185, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1239, in his hometown, at the age of 74, and was buried in Wiggenhall St Peter, Norfolk, England."},"et":{"1165–1239":"1165–1239","1164–Male":"1164–Surnud","1169–1201":"1169–1201","1185–1227":"1185–1227","1140–1165":"1140–1165","1145–1219":"1145–1219","1165":"1165","1164":"1164","1185":"1185","1140":"1140","1239":"1239","1227":"1227","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1169":"1169","1201":"1201","1145":"1145","before 1185":"enne 1185","1219":"1219","England":"England","Wiggenhall Saint Peter, Norfolk, England":"Wiggenhall St Peter, Norfolk, England","Wiggenhall St Peter, Norfolk, England":"Wiggenhall St Peter, Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"1165–1239":"1165–1239","1164–Male":"1164–Kuollut","1169–1201":"1169–1201","1185–1227":"1185–1227","1140–1165":"1140–1165","1145–1219":"1145–1219","1165":"1165","1164":"1164","1185":"1185","1140":"1140","1239":"1239","1227":"1227","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1169":"1169","1201":"1201","1145":"1145","before 1185":"ennen vuotta 1185","1219":"1219","England":"England","Wiggenhall Saint Peter, Norfolk, England":"Wiggenhall St Peter, Norfolk, England","Wiggenhall St Peter, Norfolk, England":"Wiggenhall St Peter, Norfolk, England"},"fr":{"1165–1239":"1165–1239","1164–Male":"1164–Décédé","1169–1201":"1169–1201","1185–1227":"1185–1227","1140–1165":"1140–1165","1145–1219":"1145–1219","1165":"1165","1164":"1164","1185":"1185","1140":"1140","1239":"1239","1227":"1227","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1169":"1169","1201":"1201","1145":"1145","before 1185":"avant 1185","1219":"1219","England":"Angleterre","Wiggenhall Saint Peter, Norfolk, England":"Wiggenhall St Peter, Norfolk, Angleterre","Wiggenhall St Peter, Norfolk, England":"Wiggenhall St Peter, Norfolk, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Alan Howard est né en 1165, à Wiggenhall St Peter, Norfolk, Angleterre, son père, Galfridus Howa